Importantly, Thompson acknowledges that making the abundance agenda work re=
quires a reframing of threats into benefits. He concludes:
This is an unabashedly utopian vision. But moving from venting to inventing=
, from zero-sum skirmishes over status to positive-sum solutions for Americ=
an greatness, requires not just a laundry list of marginal improvements but=
 also a defense of progress and growth. The abundance agenda aims for growt=
h, not because growth is an end but because it is the best means to achieve=
 the ends that we care about: more comfortable lives, with more power to do=
 what we want, with more time devoted to what we love.
We don=E2=80=99t just need technical advances, we need a shift towards opti=
mism.=C2=A0
American Dynamism=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a lot the government can do to create the conditions for ab=
undance: pass laws to increase the number of physicians, fund R&D, cut the =
red tape that makes nuclear plants so expensive to build, change zoning law=
s to encourage development, and much more.=C2=A0
But the government won=E2=80=99t be able to innovate alone; it=E2=80=99s no=
t what it does best. Katherine Boyle, who runs a16z=E2=80=99s American Dyna=
mism [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhCAQRL9muI1BBcUDh73sb5gGWoe=
MgoFmN_794njYhJCQoqu6ngXCNaZTHzETu66ZzgN1wN-8IREmVjKm2TvdDp3qpZiY08K1Sirm87=
wkxB38pikVZEcxm7dAPobPBOedZC8thRGwmHaxE4xjtTEwAQ4KpZoQrLlzoTiPwaLGH0xnDMhs3=
HcMdFmxTb-Ijvzovx7ddz1LoZKwqV_qwxS_OR_WJ-yY6gLh6c4Au8-XyLzueNfxgU-t4FwOTd9Y=
6wyMvUEJOMqBPwTf167JxWQC-75sWdIhkomp-lb5_are20eoLedrtRI8nTMGMBu6GwDdHD9I5hU=
DpsrXzUCVnhSj6tWoJtnehWstqYauMhWsJrtYp8J_6B_jX4zG ] practice, believes that=
 the government should work more closely with startups to address the natio=
n=E2=80=99s biggest challenges.=C2=A0
Boyle has been hitting the press circuit recently, with a Noah Smith interv=
iew [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMuOgzAMRb-m2RWFvAiLLEYa9TdQHgai=
QoJC6Ii_H7csRiPF2Vz7Xvt4W2HK5TRb3it5f0M9NzAJfvYFaoVCjh3KEINpFdNcip4EI0KrpSZ=
xH8YCsNq4mFoOINvhluhtjTl9JihlksyGQec6bb0ae67Gjou-k0LpMTBvwXtx5dojREgeDLygnD=
kB8XldIdW3FVnMXOu23_jXjT3wpWznLSZMavbD7dX6Z4P9qGxYMeHmrwg_96etM5SY4O7yucD9h=
YZHgRt_oNd3IdEwyhhVtG8FpVI1vPE-ONtxB9JCJxW9CbpO7F8MKSbl6jIaTyg_Z7vC8hEQwfDe=
-0ixngMk6xYIF516Qf7wGiZIUBB-GGxFtFJ0mutO97K9aODNUiuGwAXB5JBxKv2F_gKWBZbv ] =
and a conversation with Ben & David on Acquired [ https://email.mg2.substac=
k.com/c/eJxFkclqwzAQhp_GutXIkuXloENKSFtoboG0J6NlbKuxJSPJbZ2nr5IcCsMwzPYz3yg=
RYXB-44sLEd1cF7cFuIWfMEGM4NEawHdG86IiDWVlizQvddGwBpnQ9R5gFmbi0a-AllVORolonL=
1PYEwYGrko6qLvZVkqohmThVKUVULqVrWkoBQ_dMWqDVgFHL7Bb84CUm6ewcbbKjTxMcYlZHSXk=
UMyt4DNw-Ki6bc8NaYULCY4DSliZHu7OsKuIz3buR33H7_k5ZjRQzAZ3R-hPe8_O39aDHs_Vc-v=
Xx9Pww4ZTjAhuMJtUWLMqpzmSmkpaiqBCahZhbMSzwPJwypDFOpy00WeWxel88YOqXwZxQzTvZB=
gdLcLVmvi1oEVcgL94BQfuO_kugEs-PQG3YmYILOybmhTNy0rHlzS9aypSEJfoqSsXZqy_6J_Bc=
aXYQ ]. Her message is clear: the only way to reverse America=E2=80=99s rec=
ent stagnation and kickstart innovation post-COVID is through =E2=80=9Ctech=
nologists building companies that support the national interest.=E2=80=9D
She, too, acknowledges that technological progress is an important piece of=
 the puzzle, but that, =E2=80=9Cmost importantly, dynamism requires optimis=
m and a belief in growth and opportunity.=E2=80=9D
While her solution is different from, or at least complementary to, Thompso=
n=E2=80=99s, both agree that a re-ignition of optimism and a renewed apprec=
iation in progress and growth are critical elements to any plan that would =
create abundance.=C2=A0
Whatever the specific solution, it=E2=80=99s time for pessimism to subside =
and optimism to thrive. In the interview with Smith, Boyle hands the pen ov=
er to David Foster Wallace, who pointed out the declining usefulness of iro=
ny, as captured in Stephen J. Burn=E2=80=99s Conversations with David Foste=
r Wallace [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM1u7CAMhZ8mLCPCX2DBolU1iy=
7aLlpV6iYi4GTQJBAR0ij36S-ZWVSyLNnY5-DPmgxjTIde4prRmbp8LKAD7OsEOUNC2wqp8043g=
kjKmUJOM9dILpFfuyEBzMZPOqcN0LL1k7cm-xjuGxgTjq5aSUUZxYoMSkgjGqHagQ2CDI1kFox4=
-JrNeQgWNPxCOmIAZOM8Q8inFJr0NedlrehTRS4l9n2vzWz-xVCXsdJwS0nPGLcfb--vP9_nFL1=
0RTA6H8aKvnx9XmRFRJ9vqVQN8ppgQrDAqmEYc1HT2lrXm5b2wA20XOCK4Xkk9br1azb2djqhpE=
PMfUynKMO3q5lhuj-U47vzx1vw-SjGpp_APbjkB947qW6EAKlgd53JBSpnraSylYo3Dw7lWi4FK=
agZKs4ulq3wZ_ofbG-P1A ]:
Irony=E2=80=99s useful for debunking illusions, but most of the illusion-de=
bunking in the U.S. has now been done and redone=E2=80=A6All we seem to wan=
t to do is keep ridiculing the stuff. Postmodern irony and cynicism=E2=80=
=99s become an end in itself, a measure of hip sophistication and literary =
savvy. Few artists dare to try to talk about ways of working toward redeemi=
ng what=E2=80=99s wrong, because they=E2=80=99ll look sentimental and naive=
 to all the weary ironists. Irony=E2=80=99s gone from liberating to enslavi=
ng.
If you=E2=80=99ve spent any time on Twitter, or your social media platform =
of choice, you recognize the truth in DFW=E2=80=99s observation. It=E2=80=
=99s another way of saying that pessimists seem smart, and optimists seem n=
aive. But the facts support the optimists, and culture needs to shift to su=
pport them as well, not to avoid a terrible future (although a more cynical=
 future sounds terrible), but to create a much better one.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The optimists aren=E2=80=99t always going to get things right, and even whe=
n they do, it=E2=80=99s not ever going to be easy. It=E2=80=99s going to be=
 hard. Abrams concludes the video I shared above by saying, =E2=80=9CThis i=
s a story about ambition. About the sheer audacity that it=E2=80=99s gonna =
take to get to where we need to go.=E2=80=9D Strong =E2=80=9Cnot because it=
 is easy, but because it is hard=E2=80=9D vibes. We need a lot more of that=
 at every level.=C2=A0
I asked people on Twitter what made them most optimistic about the next dec=
ade, and received answers ranging from =E2=80=9Cmy kids=E2=80=9D to the COV=
ID vaccine effort to remote work to DNA sequencing to nuclear fusion:
There=E2=80=99s a lot to be optimistic about if you=E2=80=99re looking. At =
Not Boring, we=E2=80=99re going to keep investing in and telling the storie=
s of the optimists, the people and companies who are making much of what we=
=E2=80=99ve discussed a reality. We=E2=80=99ll be realistic and acknowledge=
 challenges, of course, but focus more of our attention on what the world l=
ooks like if things go right. There are more than enough cynics out there t=
o counterbalance my optimism.=C2=A0
And I want to do more. One idea: let me know if you=E2=80=99d be interested=
 in a weekly roundup of optimistic stories, a tiny pushback against the doo=
msday headlines that blanket most media homepages. I=E2=80=99d love to hear=
 your ideas, too. Reply to my tweet on this article at @packym [ https://em=
ail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQhU_TLA0gKC5YzGZ2cwbCT7VNWsFAOR1vP6iLSUgl=
pOrVq-95izDncugtVyRnMXhsoBN86gKIUMheoZgYNBu46qWYSNAiMCUVidU8C8Bq46Kx7EC23S3=
RW4w5XQpKuSQvLcXYA58kjFR45ygTzHlLh-fAOJ2e9Pa1e4iQPGj4hXLkBMTndYWE5yqy6BfiVh=
_914N_t4efeF7XtZn226x_Hz8kak45pwOdmKBUDl3feR-cHXsH0sIoB_oQdJ15V3dXsYlOPSk6Z=
XS5xDS39vtlV1iuRuMx5xF7ingYSNYtEG5UvBO74M0MCUpLMhiLLafGq3o1qkmyG60BSDXwlp4g=
zTnkpkr_pn9JVYN7 ] to contribute.
